<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900405-0072</DOCNO><DOCID>900405-0072.</DOCID><HL>   Hate-Crime Statistics Bill   Is Sent to Bush for Signing</HL><DATE>04/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The House gave final congressional approvalto a bill that would require the Justice Department for thefirst time to collect and publish statistics on so-calledhate crimes.   The measure, passed 402-18, now goes to President Bush,who is expected to sign it.</LP><TEXT>   Hate crimes are those motivated by prejudice based on avictim's race, religion, national origin or sexualorientation. Despite increased federal investigation andprosecution of such crimes, they have persisted in recentyears and may have even increased, according to surveysconducted by various private organizations.   &quot;Many would say the problem has escalated,&quot; said Rep.Barbara Kennelly (D., Conn.), a leading sponsor of thelegislation. The bill would require the Justice Department tocollect hate crime statistics and publish them annually sothat federal, state and local law-enforcement officials canmeasure trends and deploy resources more effectively.</TEXT></DOC>